### Description
In OpenSSL 4.0, `EVP_SignFinal()` no longer respects per-key method overrides attached to asymmetric key objects. This breaks integrations that rely on documented per-key method overrides attached to asymmetric key objects. When a key is wrapped in an `EVP_PKEY`, `EVP_SignFinal()` appears to bypass the key’s attached method and instead performs the operation using the default internal implementation.

This is a behavioral regression relative to historical OpenSSL behavior.

### Expected behavior
If an EVP_PKEY contains an asymmetric key object (RSA*, EC_KEY*, etc.) with a custom per-key method attached, then:
- high-level signing APIs such as `EVP_SignFinal(`) should honor that method
- the custom callbacks (e.g. priv_enc, sign) should be invoked.

This behavior is required for backward compatibility of non-provider code.

### Actual behavior
- Low-level APIs (`RSA_sign()`, `ECDSA_sign()`) correctly invoke the custom per-key methods
- `EVP_SignFinal()` does not invoke the custom per-key methods
- instead, the default internal implementation is used.

This indicates that `EVP_SignFinal()` no longer operates on the original key object, or otherwise discards its attached method.
This strongly suggests that EVP_SignFinal() no longer performs signing operations via the underlying key object.

### Minimal reproducer (RSA)
The following minimal PoC installs a custom `RSA_METHOD` that increments a counter when the private operation is invoked.

Observed output on Fedora 43 with OpenSSL 4.0.0-dev:
```
After RSA_sign():      priv_enc_hits=1
After EVP_SignFinal(): priv_enc_hits=0
```
This shows that`EVP_SignFinal()` bypasses the custom per-key method.

No providers are loaded or used in this reproducer.

### Proof of Concept
```c
#define OPENSSL_SUPPRESS_DEPRECATED
#include <stdio.h>
#include <openssl/evp.h>
#include <openssl/rsa.h>
#include <openssl/sha.h>

static int priv_enc_hits = 0;
static int (*orig_priv_enc)(int, const unsigned char *, unsigned char *, RSA *, int);

static int my_priv_enc(int flen, const unsigned char *from, unsigned char *to,
                       RSA *rsa, int padding)
{
    priv_enc_hits++;
    return orig_priv_enc(flen, from, to, rsa, padding);
}

int main(void)
{
    const unsigned char msg[] = "abc";
    unsigned char sig[256], md[SHA256_DIGEST_LENGTH];
    unsigned int siglen;

    BIGNUM *e = BN_new();
    BN_set_word(e, RSA_F4);

    RSA *rsa = RSA_new();
    RSA_generate_key_ex(rsa, 2048, e, NULL);
    BN_free(e);

    const RSA_METHOD *def = RSA_get_default_method();
    RSA_METHOD *method = RSA_meth_dup(def);

    orig_priv_enc = RSA_meth_get_priv_enc(def);
    RSA_meth_set_priv_enc(method, my_priv_enc);
    RSA_set_method(rsa, method);

    EVP_PKEY *pkey = EVP_PKEY_new();
    EVP_PKEY_assign_RSA(pkey, rsa);

    priv_enc_hits = 0;
    SHA256(msg, sizeof(msg) - 1, md);
    RSA_sign(NID_sha256, md, SHA256_DIGEST_LENGTH, sig, &siglen, rsa);
    printf("After RSA_sign():\tpriv_enc_hits=%d\n", priv_enc_hits);

    priv_enc_hits = 0;
    EVP_MD_CTX *ctx = EVP_MD_CTX_new();
    EVP_SignInit(ctx, EVP_sha256());
    EVP_SignUpdate(ctx, msg, sizeof(msg) - 1);
    EVP_SignFinal(ctx, sig, &siglen, pkey);
    EVP_MD_CTX_free(ctx);
    printf("After EVP_SignFinal():\tpriv_enc_hits=%d\n", priv_enc_hits);

    EVP_PKEY_free(pkey);
    RSA_meth_free(method);
    return 0;
}
```

### Suspected cause
While PR #29384 removed support for custom EVP_PKEY_METHODs, it does not document or justify bypassing per-key methods such as RSA_METHOD or EC_KEY_METHOD.

### Documentation reference
Current [RSA_set_method](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/master/doc/man3/RSA_set_method.pod) documentation still states:
> RSA_set_method() selects meth to perform all operations using the key rsa. This will replace the RSA_METHOD used by the RSA key.

The documented behavior directly contradicts the observed behavior in OpenSSL 4.0.0-dev.

### Note on EC / ECDSA
The same behavior can be reproduced with EC keys by overriding `EC_KEY_METHOD` sign callbacks:
- `ECDSA_sign()` invokes the custom method
- `EVP_SignFinal()` does not.

This demonstrates that the issue is not specific to RSA, but affects per-key methods across asymmetric algorithms.

### Impact
Real-world applications use documented per-key method overrides to redirect, instrument, or constrain private key operations on a per-key basis. When `EVP_SignFinal()` bypasses these methods while low-level API functions still invoke them, application behavior becomes inconsistent and silently incorrect.

### Regression note
This behavior appears to be an unintentional regression caused by removal of legacy paths.
There is no indication that ignoring per-key methods in `EVP_SignFinal()` was an intentional or documented change.

## Summary

The optimized NIST prime curve implementations (`nistp224`, `nistp256`, `nistp384`, and `nistp521`) are missing a simple but important optimization check when converting points from Jacobian to affine coordinates. Specifically, they fail to check if the Z coordinate is already 1 before performing expensive field inversion and multiplication operations.

## Affected Functions

- `ossl_ec_GFp_nistp224_point_get_affine_coordinates()` in `crypto/ec/ecp_nistp224.c`
- `ossl_ec_GFp_nistp256_point_get_affine_coordinates()` in `crypto/ec/ecp_nistp256.c`
- `ossl_ec_GFp_nistp384_point_get_affine_coordinates()` in `crypto/ec/ecp_nistp384.c`
- `ossl_ec_GFp_nistp521_point_get_affine_coordinates()` in `crypto/ec/ecp_nistp521.c`

## Description

### Current Behavior

The current implementations of `point_get_affine_coordinates()` for all NIST prime curves (P-224, P-256/secp256r1, P-384, and P-521) unconditionally perform expensive operations when converting from Jacobian coordinates (X, Y, Z) to affine coordinates (x, y).

For example, in `crypto/ec/ecp_nistp256.c` lines 1936-1975:

```c
int ossl_ec_GFp_nistp256_point_get_affine_coordinates(const EC_GROUP *group,
    const EC_POINT *point,
    BIGNUM *x, BIGNUM *y,
    BN_CTX *ctx)
{
    felem z1, z2, x_in, y_in;
    smallfelem x_out, y_out;
    longfelem tmp;

    if (EC_POINT_is_at_infinity(group, point)) {
        ERR_raise(ERR_LIB_EC, EC_R_POINT_AT_INFINITY);
        return 0;
    }
    if ((!BN_to_felem(x_in, point->X)) || (!BN_to_felem(y_in, point->Y)) || (!BN_to_felem(z1, point->Z)))
        return 0;
    felem_inv(z2, z1);           // ALWAYS performs expensive inversion
    felem_square(tmp, z2);
    felem_reduce(z1, tmp);
    felem_mul(tmp, x_in, z1);
    felem_reduce(x_in, tmp);
    felem_contract(x_out, x_in);
    // ... (rest of the function)
}
```

### Expected Behavior

The reference implementation `ossl_ec_GFp_simple_point_get_affine_coordinates()` in `crypto/ec/ecp_smpl.c` (lines 539-558) correctly handles the case where Z = 1:

```c
if (BN_is_one(Z_)) {
    if (group->meth->field_decode != NULL) {
        if (x != NULL) {
            if (!group->meth->field_decode(group, x, point->X, ctx))
                goto err;
        }
        if (y != NULL) {
            if (!group->meth->field_decode(group, y, point->Y, ctx))
                goto err;
        }
    } else {
        if (x != NULL) {
            if (!BN_copy(x, point->X))
                goto err;
        }
        if (y != NULL) {
            if (!BN_copy(y, point->Y))
                goto err;
        }
    }
} else {
    // perform full Jacobian-to-affine conversion
}
```

When Z = 1, the point is already in affine form, so the affine coordinates are simply (x, y) = (X, Y), requiring no inversions or multiplications.


## Proposed Fix

Add a check for Z = 1 at the beginning of each `nistp*_point_get_affine_coordinates()` function, similar to the simple implementation. For P-256 specifically:

```c
int ossl_ec_GFp_nistp256_point_get_affine_coordinates(const EC_GROUP *group,
    const EC_POINT *point,
    BIGNUM *x, BIGNUM *y,
    BN_CTX *ctx)
{
    felem z1, z2, x_in, y_in;
    smallfelem x_out, y_out;
    longfelem tmp;

    if (EC_POINT_is_at_infinity(group, point)) {
        ERR_raise(ERR_LIB_EC, EC_R_POINT_AT_INFINITY);
        return 0;
    }

    // NEW: Check if Z = 1 (point already in affine form)
    if (BN_is_one(point->Z)) {
        if (x != NULL) {
            if (!BN_copy(x, point->X)) {
                ERR_raise(ERR_LIB_EC, ERR_R_BN_LIB);
                return 0;
            }
        }
        if (y != NULL) {
            if (!BN_copy(y, point->Y)) {
                ERR_raise(ERR_LIB_EC, ERR_R_BN_LIB);
                return 0;
            }
        }
        return 1;
    }

    // Original expensive conversion for Z != 1
    if ((!BN_to_felem(x_in, point->X)) || (!BN_to_felem(y_in, point->Y)) || (!BN_to_felem(z1, point->Z)))
        return 0;
    felem_inv(z2, z1);
    felem_square(tmp, z2);
    felem_reduce(z1, tmp);
    felem_mul(tmp, x_in, z1);
    felem_reduce(x_in, tmp);
    felem_contract(x_out, x_in);
    if (x != NULL) {
        if (!smallfelem_to_BN(x, x_out)) {
            ERR_raise(ERR_LIB_EC, ERR_R_BN_LIB);
            return 0;
        }
    }
    felem_mul(tmp, z1, z2);
    felem_reduce(z1, tmp);
    felem_mul(tmp, y_in, z1);
    felem_reduce(y_in, tmp);
    felem_contract(y_out, y_in);
    if (y != NULL) {
        if (!smallfelem_to_BN(y, y_out)) {
            ERR_raise(ERR_LIB_EC, ERR_R_BN_LIB);
            return 0;
        }
    }
    return 1;
}
```

The same fix should be applied to `nistp224`, `nistp384`, and `nistp521`.

